Tutorial lab

Linear Regression - predict automobile vehicle insurance claims costs

Motivation

  • insurers invest time and money to develop models that accurately forecast claims costs for the insured population
    • This is the field known as actuarial science
    • uses sophisticated statistical techniques to estimate risk
  • If the expense estimates for each risk segment are correct
    • the insurance company can price the insurance premiums lower for segments with less risk
    • and potentially attract new, low-risk customers from competing insurance companies

Step 1 - collect data

  • a simulation based on demographics and traffic statistics from the United States government

    • approximate the real-world conditions of automobile insurance companies in the U.S. state of Michigan
      • home to about ten million residents and seven million licensed drivers

  • 20,000 cases of beneficiaries enrolled in the hypothetical automobile vehicle insurance plan

  • Each case represents an insured individualâs characteristics and total insurance claims costs (expenses) charged to the plan for the calendar year

  • each of the 20,000 beneficiaries enrolled in a âsafe driving discountâ program

    • required the use of a device or mobile phone application
    • monitor safe driving conditions throughout the year

Step 1 - collect data

  • The features available at the time of enrollment are:
    • age: The age of the driver, from 16 to 89
    • geo_area: The geographic area of the vehicle ownerâs primary residence
      • the place where the vehicle will be used most often
    • est_value: The estimated market value of the vehicle(s)
    • vehicle_type: The type of passenger vehicle, either a car, truck, minivan, or sport utility vehicle (SUV)
    • miles_driven: The distance driven (in miles) in the calendar year
    • college_grad_ind: A binary indicator set to 1 if the beneficiary has a college education or higher
    • speeding_ticket_ind: A binary indicator set to 1 if a speeding ticket or infraction was received during the past five years
    • clean_driving_ind: A binary indicator set to 1 if no at-fault insurance claims were paid during the past five years

More varaibles

  • the following two additional predictors, which are intended to reflect more risky driving behaviors:

    • hard_braking_ind
      • A binary indicator set to 1 if the vehicle frequently applies âhard brakesâ
    • late_driving_ind
      • A binary indicator set to 1 if the vehicle is driven regularly after midnight

  • A regression model will help us disentangle relationships among those variables

  • It requires us to specify the connections between the features ourselves

    • vs detecting them automatically

  • unlike many other machine learning methods

  • Gender is often used for automobile insurance pricing (and it varies whether males or females are more costly!)

  • but the state of Michigan banned the use of gender and credit scoring for this purpose in 2020

  • Such features may be highly predictive, but may lead to systematic biases against protected groups

Visualizing relationships between features â the scatterplot matrix

Code 
#install.packages("psych")

library(psych)

pairs.panels(insurance[c("age", "est_value", "miles_driven", "expenses")], pch=".")
  • In the pairs.panels() output,
    • the scatterplots above the diagonal are replaced with a correlation matrix
    • The diagonal now contains histograms depicting the distribution of values for each feature
    • the scatterplots below the diagonal are presented with additional visual information
  • a correlation ellipse

    • provides a simple visual indicator of correlation strength

    • In this dataset, there are no strong correlations, so the ovals are mostly flat

    • with stronger correlations, the ovals would be tilted upward or downward to indicate a positive or negative correlation

    • The dot at the center of the ellipse is a point reflecting the means of the x- and y-axis variables

  • The line superimposed across the scatterplot (which appears in red on a computer screen) is called a loess curve
    • It indicates the general relationship between the x-axis and y-axis variables
    • the loess curve can sometimes be quite dramatic with V- or U-shaped curves as well as stairstep patterns
    • Recognizing such patterns can assist later with developing a better-fitting regression model

Step 3 - Training a model

run a regression model

Code 
ins_model<- lm(expenses~ age + geo_area + vehicle_type + 
                 est_value + miles_driven + 
                 college_grad_ind + speeding_ticket_ind + 
                 hard_braking_ind + late_driving_ind +
                 clean_driving_ind,
               data=insurance)

options(scipen=999)

Step 5 - Improve model performance

  • adding a nonlinear relationship for age

  • adding interaction effects

  • a habit of hard braking and late driving may have harmful effects separately

  • but it is reasonable to assume that their combined effect may be worse than the sum of each one alone

  • When two features have a combined effect, this is known as an interaction

Code 
insurance$age2<- insurance$age^2

ins_model2<- lm(expenses ~ .+ hard_braking_ind:late_driving_ind,
                data=insurance)

summary(ins_model2)

Housing Example

Predicting house prices using Boston housing data

Some information about the data

  • The Boston housing dataset is a classic dataset used in regression analysis
  • It contains 506 observations on housing prices in the Boston area
  • The dataset has 12(3) features and 1 target variable
  • The features include:
    • crim: per capita crime rate by town
    • zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq. ft.
    • indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town
    • chas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
    • nox: nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
    • rm: average number of rooms per dwelling
    • age: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
    • dis: weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
    • rad: index of accessibility to radial highways
    • tax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
    • ptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town
    • lstat: % lower status of the population
  • The target variable is the median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s (medv)
